/run/dbus/system_bus_socket\n\n**Short answer – the listening port in the list 
is `5432`.**\n\n---\n\n### Why you see a *huge* list\n\n`netstat -antp` (or `ss 
-tuln`) shows *every* TCP socket that exists on the host:\n\n| Column | What it 
is |\n|--------|------------|\n| `Proto` | Protocol (TCP, UDP) |\n| `Recv-Q` / 
`Send-Q` | Queued packets (usually 0) |\n| `Local Address:Port` | The socket’s 
own address/port |\n| `Foreign Address:Port` | Where the socket is connected to 
(or *\\*** if not connected) |\n| `State` | Connection state (`ESTABLISHED`, 
`LISTEN`, `CLOSE_WAIT`, etc.) |\n| `PID/Program name` | Who owns the socket 
(only if you run as root) |\n\nBecause a container shares the host’s network 
stack (unless it’s running in its own network namespace), every socket opened by
the container appears in the host’s output.\n\n---\n\n### Finding the listening 
port\n\nIn the output you posted, the *first* line that starts with `LISTEN` is 
the only one where the socket is **listening** for incoming 
connections:\n\n```\n  tcp        0      0 192.168.1.2:5432   0.0.0.0:*         
LISTENING   1114/postgres\n```\n\n- **Local address** – `192.168.1.2` (the 
container’s IP on the host network)\n- **Port** – `5432`\n- **State** – 
`LISTENING` (so it’s waiting for connections)\n\nThat’s the port you’re looking 
for.\n\n---\n\n### Quick ways to spot listening sockets\n\nIf you just want the 
listening sockets (and optionally the owning process), run one of 
these:\n\n```bash\n# Show all listening TCP sockets (needs root for 
PID/Program)\nsudo netstat -tlnp\n\n# Or the newer, faster tool:\nsudo ss 
-tlnp\n```\n\nOutput example:\n\n```\nNetid  State      Recv-Q Send-Q  Local 
Address:Port   Peer Address:Port  Process\ntcp    LISTEN     0      128     
192.168.1.2:5432     0.0.0.0:*         1114/postgres\n```\n\nYou can further 
filter by the container ID (if you know it):\n\n```bash\nsudo ss -tlnp | grep 
1114   # 1114 is the PID of postgres in the container\n```\n\n---\n\n### If you 
want to see *only* the container’s ports\n\nIf you’re using Docker, the simplest
way to find which host port maps to a container port is:\n\n```bash\ndocker port
<container-id>\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```bash\ndocker port my-postgres\n# => 
5432/tcp -> 0.0.0.0:5432\n```\n\nIf the container is in a user‑defined bridge 
network, you’ll see something like:\n\n```\n5432/tcp -> 
192.168.1.2:5432\n```\n\n---\n\n### TL;DR\n\n- The line beginning with `LISTEN` 
shows the listening socket.\n- The port number there (`5432`) is the one the 
container is listening on.\n- Use `ss -tlnp` or `netstat -tlnp` to filter for 
listening sockets quickly.\n- With Docker, `docker port <container-id>` gives 
the mapping cleanly.\n\nFeel free to run the filtered commands on your host; 
